#2a
setwd("~/Downloads")
df1 <- read.csv("toenail-data.csv")
#2b
#for group treatment = 1
miss1=c()
miss0=c()
df_treat = df1[(df1$Treatment==1),]
df_control = df1[(df1$Treatment==0),]
for (i in 1:7){
    miss1[i] = 1-nrow(df_treat[(df_treat$Visit==i),])/length(unique(df_treat$ID))
}
for (i in 1:7){
    miss0[i] = 1-nrow(df_control[(df_control$Visit==i),])/length(unique(df_control$ID))
}

miss = cbind(miss1,miss0)
colnames(miss) = c('treatment_miss','control_miss')
rownames(miss) = c('0week','4week','8week','12week','24week','36week','48week')
miss

#2c
#Get proportions of Y=1 by treatment group at each time point
df1$Week=as.integer(as.character(factor(df1$Visit,level=c(1:7),labels=c(0,4,8,12,24,36,48))))
df_obs = aggregate(df1$Y, list(df1$Treatment, df1$Week), mean, na.rm=T)
names(df_obs) = c("tx","week","p")
#Calculate odds and log-odds
df_obs$odds = df_obs$p/(1-df_obs$p)
df_obs$logit = log(df_obs$odds)
#change treatment to two factor
df_obs$tx = factor(df_obs$tx, levels = c(0,1),
                         labels = c('placebo','drug'))
library(ggplot2)
p1 = ggplot(df_obs, aes(x=week,y=p,group=tx))
p1 + geom_line(aes(color=tx)) + geom_point(aes(color=tx)) +
  labs(title="Observed Proportions by Treatment Group over Time",
color="Treatment", y="Proportion of Moderate/severe diease")

observed probability of moderate/severe onycholysis over weeks of follow up, with the increase of the week the probability will decrease as well. the treatment group will be slightly less than the placebo group.

#2d
p2 = ggplot(df_obs, aes(x=week,y=logit,group=tx))
p2 + geom_line(aes(color=tx)) + geom_point(aes(color=tx)) +
  labs(title="Observed Proportions by Treatment Group over Time",
color="Treatment", y="Log Proportion of Moderate/severe diease")

observed probability of log moderate/severe onycholysis over weeks of follow up, with the increase of the week the treatment group probability will decrease as well. But the placebo group will increase after week 35. the treatment group will be slightly less than the placebo group.

3a

Equation:

Logit(E(Yij|bi)) = beta1 + beta2treatmenti +beta3 weekij + beta4treatmentweekij +bij

3b

Assumptions:

  1. Random effects come from a normal distribution bi~N(0,sigma^2)

2.The chosen link function is appropriate.

3.estimation of variance should be proper.

3c

Link function:

g(ui) = log(ui/(1-ui))=logit(ui) so the function is logit.

3d

Liknear predictor:

ni = beta1+beta2treatment+ beta3 weekij + beta4treatmentweekij

H0: beta2/beta3/beta4 = 0 Ha:beta2/beta3/beta4 != 0 As a result, Use anova. the final model is m1. Since the p value is 0.8447> 0.05.

##3e ii

(Intercept) -1.63069 , so estimate for the intercept of this model: uij = exp(-1.63069)/(1+exp(-1.63069))

##3e iii since in the model with week and interaction, we done the summary above, The intercept is -1.68676 ,Week -0.10057, Treatweek -0.04138 so Logit(E(Yij|bi)) = beta1 + beta2treatmenti + beta4treatment*weekij +bij

the beta2 means each unit increase in week changes of log-odds will change by -0.10057 for unique individual with response positively equal to b1i.

the beta3 means each unit increase in weektreatment changes of log-odds will change by -0.04138 for unique individual with response positively equal to b1i.

#3e iv.
df1$m1_pred <- predict(m1, newdata=df1, type="response") 
df1$m1_pred2 <- predict(m1, newdata=df1, type="response", ReForm=NA)
## Warning: 'ReForm' is deprecated; use 're.form' instead
t_pred <- df1[,c('m1_pred2','Treatment','Week')] 
m1_pred <- unique(t_pred)
names(m1_pred) <- c("pred","t","week") 
m1_pred$odds <- m1_pred$pred/(1-m1_pred$pred) 
m1_pred$logit <- log(m1_pred$odds)
m1_pred <- m1_pred[order(m1_pred$week,m1_pred$t),] 
print(m1_pred)

The response probability of risk is decreasing with the increase of week. And the log odds is from -5 to -10. The treatment group is slightly less than the control group. which means the treatment has a moderate effect.

#vi
increase =c()
increase[1] = exp(m1_pred$logit[2]-m1_pred$logit[1])
increase[2] = exp(m1_pred$logit[4]-m1_pred$logit[3])
increase[3] = exp(m1_pred$logit[6]-m1_pred$logit[5])
increase[4] = exp(m1_pred$logit[8]-m1_pred$logit[7])
increase[5] = exp(m1_pred$logit[10]-m1_pred$logit[9])
increase[6] = exp(m1_pred$logit[12]-m1_pred$logit[11])
increase[7] = exp(m1_pred$logit[14]-m1_pred$logit[13])

      
week <- c(0,4,8,12,24,36,48)
new <- as.data.frame(cbind(week,increase))
pvi <- ggplot(new, aes(x=week,y=increase))
pvi + geom_line() + geom_point()+labs(title="Predicted Odds" ,color="Treatment", y="Increased Odds of Y=1")

Estimate subject-specific ratios of increased odds of moderate/severe onycholysis across time (weeks 0, 4,8,12,24,36, 48) in subjects randomized to Terbinafine relative to the subjects randomized to Itraconazole. The week increase, the increased odds decreases.

##3 evii What missing data mechanism assumption for the outcome was used in your GLMM to obtain parameter estimates? What do we need to assume about the joint distribution of the outcomes and the model for the mean response to have unbiased parameter estimates?

we need to assume the missing data are random. and the residuals are normal distribution.
